{:proof/problem-id "apm-a93J02", :proof/classification :partial, :proof/output "\n\n---\n\nTARGET SANITY CHECK — mentions-problem-objects? ✅ (it explicitly features the alternating harmonic series, the function \\(f(x)=1/(1+x)\\), and DCT hypotheses) · avoids-assuming-conclusion? ✅ (the Lean target asserts summability and equality but does not presume them) · meaningful-without-prose? ✅ (even without the writeup it is a stand-alone analytic theorem) · notes: We will prove the geometric-series integral via dominated convergence, so certifying the tsum identity is exactly what Mathlib needs.\n\n```\nPROOF-PLAN.EDN\n{:goal \"Use dominated convergence on the Taylor series of (1+x)^{-1} over [0,1] to justify rigorously that the alternating harmonic series sums to log 2.\"\n :terms [{:name \"dominated convergence theorem\"\n          :meaning \"Allows interchange of limit (here an infinite sum) and integral when the summands are dominated by an integrable function.\"\n          :needed-because \"We want to integrate a pointwise-convergent series term-by-term.\"}\n         {:name \"power-series expansion of (1+x)^{-1}\"\n          :meaning \"For |x|<1, (1+x)^{-1} = \\\\sum_{n=0}^\\\\infty (-1)^n x^n.\"\n          :needed-because \"Provides the functions whose integrals produce the alternating harmonic series.\"}\n         {:name \"integrable dominator on [0,1]\"\n          :meaning \"Choose a simple integrable function (e.g., g(x)=1) that bounds every summand uniformly in n.\"\n          :needed-because \"DCT requires a single integrable bound independent of n.\"}]\n :strategy [{:id :s1\n             :formal-dependency \"Power-series identity for the reciprocal\"\n             :informal-dependency \"Stage 1 observation that (1+x)^{-1} equals the geometric series on [0,1)\"\n             :why-this-now \"Relate the integral of f(x) to \\\\sum (-1)^n/(n+1) by integrating x^n over [0,1].\"\n             :lean-target \"reciprocal_one_plus_integral_series\"\n             :mathlib-status \"Mathlib already proves the geometric-series formula; only specialization is needed.\"}\n            {:id :s2\n             :formal-dependency \"Dominated convergence theorem\"\n             :informal-dependency \"Stage 1 identification of g(x)=1 as a dominator\"\n             :why-this-now \"Use DCT to justify swapping sum and integral, then compute ∫_0^1 (1+x)^{-1} dx = log 2.\"\n             :lean-target \"alternating_harmonic_sums_to_log_two\"\n             :mathlib-status \"`tendsto_integral_of_dominated_convergence` is available; need to verify measurability and domination.\"}]\n :stage-status {:stage1 :done :stage2 :done :stage3 :in-progress :stage4 :pending}}\n```\n\n```\nFORMAL-ALIGNMENT.EDN\n{:main-claim {:informal-claim \"The alternating harmonic series \\\\(\\\\sum_{n=0}^\\\\infty (-1)^n/(n+1)\\\\) equals \\\\(\\\\log 2\\\\).\"\n             :formal-name \"alternating_harmonic_tsum_log_two\"\n             :formal-target \"Tsummable (fun n : ℕ => (-1 : ℝ)^n / (n+1)) ∧ tsum (fun n : ℕ => (-1 : ℝ)^n / (n+1)) = Real.log 2\"\n             :sanity-check {:mentions-problem-objects? true\n                            :avoids-assuming-conclusion? true\n                            :meaningful-without-prose? true\n                            :notes \"States precisely that the alternating harmonic series converges (by DCT) and sums to log 2.\"}}\n :alignments [{:formal-name \"alternating_harmonic_tsum_log_two\"\n              :formal-statement \"Tsummable (fun n : ℕ => (-1 : ℝ)^n / (n+1)) ∧ tsum (fun n : ℕ => (-1 : ℝ)^n / (n+1)) = Real.log 2\"\n              :informal-clause \"Main claim that \\\\(\\\\sum (-1)^n/(n+1)=\\\\log 2\\\\).\"\n              :role :main-theorem}]}\n```\n\n---\n\nTARGET SANITY CHECK — mentions-problem-objects? ✅ (features the alternating harmonic series, the function \\(1/(1+x)\\), and the DCT hypotheses) · avoids-assuming-conclusion? ✅ (the Lean target asserts both summability and equality without presuming them) · meaningful-without-prose? ✅ (it’s a standalone analytic theorem worth proving even without the exam context) · notes: DCT is the intended tool, so encoding the exact tsum identity is the right Lean objective.\n\n```\nPROOF-PLAN.EDN\n{:goal \"Use dominated convergence on the power series of 1/(1+x) over [0,1] to justify rigorously that the alternating harmonic series sums to log 2.\"\n :terms [{:name \"dominated convergence theorem\"\n          :meaning \"Allows swapping limit/sum with integral when all summands are dominated by an integrable function.\"\n          :needed-because \"We must justify integrating the power series term-by-term.\"}\n         {:name \"geometric-series expansion\"\n          :meaning \"For |x| < 1, 1/(1+x) = Σ (-1)^n x^n.\"\n          :needed-because \"It produces the summands whose integrals are (-1)^n/(n+1).\"}\n         {:name \"uniform dominator\"\n          :meaning \"An integrable g(x) ≥ |(-1)^n x^n| on [0,1] (take g≡1).\"\n          :needed-because \"DCT requires a single integrable bound independent of n.\"}]\n :strategy [{:id :s1\n             :formal-dependency \"Geometric-series identity for |x| < 1\"\n             :informal-dependency \"Stage 1 rewrite of f(x) as Σ (-1)^n x^n\"\n             :why-this-now \"Turning the integral of 1/(1+x) into Σ ∫ x^n allows us to identify the alternating harmonic terms.\"\n             :lean-target \"one_plus_geom_series_integral\"\n             :mathlib-status \"Mathlib has `summable_geometric_of_abs_lt_1`; we only need to specialize to real x ∈ [0,1).\"}\n            {:id :s2\n             :formal-dependency \"Dominated convergence theorem\"\n             :informal-dependency \"Stage 1 choice of g(x)=1 as dominator\"\n             :why-this-now \"DCT justifies swapping sum and integral, after which the integral equals log 2.\"\n             :lean-target \"alternating_harmonic_tsum_log_two\"\n             :mathlib-status \"`tendsto_integral_of_dominated_convergence` exists; measurability and domination are straightforward on [0,1].\"}]\n :stage-status {:stage1 :done :stage2 :done :stage3 :in-progress :stage4 :pending}}\n```\n\n```\nFORMAL-ALIGNMENT.EDN\n{:main-claim {:informal-claim \"The alternating harmonic series ∑_{n=0}^∞ (-1)^n/(n+1) converges to log 2.\"\n             :formal-name \"alternating_harmonic_tsum_log_two\"\n             :formal-target \"Tsummable (fun n : ℕ => (-1 : ℝ)^n / (n+1)) ∧ tsum (fun n : ℕ => (-1 : ℝ)^n / (n+1)) = Real.log 2\"\n             :sanity-check {:mentions-problem-objects? true\n                            :avoids-assuming-conclusion? true\n                            :meaningful-without-prose? true\n                            :notes \"Captures exactly the analytic statement we justify via dominated convergence.\"}}\n :alignments [{:formal-name \"alternating_harmonic_tsum_log_two\"\n              :formal-statement \"Tsummable (fun n : ℕ => (-1 : ℝ)^n / (n+1)) ∧ tsum (fun n : ℕ => (-1 : ℝ)^n / (n+1)) = Real.log 2\"\n              :informal-clause \"∑_{n=0}^∞ (-1)^n/(n+1) = log 2.\"\n              :role :main-theorem}]}\n```\n\n---\n\n**Why it’s hard.** Everyone remembers that the alternating harmonic series converges by the Leibniz test, so it’s tempting to wave one’s hands and declare its value to be \\(\\log 2\\) because “that’s what the Taylor series for \\(\\log(1+x)\\) says.” The trap is that interchanging an infinite sum with an integral requires hypotheses: without a convergence theorem you are simply assuming the answer.\n\n**Key insight.** Work on \\([0,1]\\) with \\(f(x)=\\frac1{1+x}\\). On that interval the geometric expansion\n\\[\n\\frac1{1+x}=\\sum_{n=0}^\\infty (-1)^n x^n\n\\]\nholds pointwise, and every summand is dominated by the integrable function \\(g(x)\\equiv 1\\). Dominated convergence therefore licenses the exchange\n\\[\n\\int_0^1 \\frac{dx}{1+x} = \\int_0^1 \\sum_{n=0}^\\infty (-1)^n x^n\\,dx = \\sum_{n=0}^\\infty \\int_0^1 (-1)^n x^n\\,dx = \\sum_{n=0}^\\infty \\frac{(-1)^n}{n+1}.\n\\]\n\n**Complete proof.**  \n1. For each \\(n\\), set \\(g_n(x)=(-1)^n x^n\\). Then \\(|g_n(x)|\\le 1\\) for \\(x\\in[0,1]\\), so \\(g(x)=1\\) dominates every \\(g_n\\) and lies in \\(L^1([0,1])\\).  \n2. The sequence of partial sums \\(S_N(x)=\\sum_{n=0}^N g_n(x)\\) converges pointwise to \\(f(x)=1/(1+x)\\). Each \\(g_n\\) (hence each \\(S_N\\)) is measurable on \\([0,1]\\).  \n3. Dominated convergence gives \\(\\int_0^1 f = \\lim_{N\\to\\infty} \\int_0^1 S_N\\).  \n4. Compute \\(\\int_0^1 g_n(x)\\,dx = (-1)^n/(n+1)\\) and \\(\\int_0^1 f(x)\\,dx=[\\log(1+x)]_0^1 = \\log 2\\).  \nThus \\(\\sum_{n=0}^\\infty (-1)^n/(n+1)=\\log 2\\).\n\n**Lean 4 formalization.**  \n- Target theorem recorded in `formal-alignment.edn` as `alternating_harmonic_tsum_log_two`.  \n- Plan (`proof-plan.edn`) splits the work into (i) expressing \\(1/(1+x)\\) as a geometric series on \\([0,1)\\) and (ii) applying `tendsto_integral_of_dominated_convergence`.  \n- Stage 3 remains in progress: we still need to mechanize the DCT instance inside `Main.lean`, show `∑ (-1)^n x^n = 1/(1+x)` via `hasSum_geometric_of_abs_lt_1`, and evaluate the integrals using `intervalIntegral`. No `sorry`s have been introduced.  \n- All narrative details (Stage 1–4) now live in `execute.md`, and `changelog.edn` logs workspace init, Stage 1/2 completion, and Stage 3’s in-progress status.\n\n**What connects.** This is the template for many prelim classics: represent a well-behaved function by a power or Fourier series, dominate the summands by something integrable, and then integrate termwise to extract special constants (e.g., \\(\\pi/4\\) from \\(\\arctan x\\), \\(\\zeta(2)\\) from \\(\\pi^2/6\\), or \\(\\log(k+1)\\) from \\(\\frac{x^k-1}{\\log x}\\)). Whenever you need a rigorous “sum equals integral” identity, your exam-day field kit should include dominated convergence, an explicit dominator, and elementary integrals of monomials.", :proof/extraction {:phases {}, :dependency-graph nil, :arse-questions nil, :classification :partial, :phase-count 0, :dep-graph-count 0, :arse-count 0}, :proof/frame-workspace {:frame/lean-root "/home/joe/code/apm-lean/ApmCanaries/Frames/A93J02/Apm_v2_a93J02_1775002596767", :frame/id "apm-v2-a93J02-1775002596767", :workspace/owner-repo "futon6", :workspace/generated-at "2026-04-01T00:16:36.789713Z", :frame/shared-extension-root "/home/joe/code/apm-lean/ApmCanaries/Local", :frame/module-root "ApmCanaries.Frames.A93J02.Apm_v2_a93J02_1775002596767", :proof/problem-id "a93J02", :workspace/schema "proof-frame-workspace.v1", :frame/workspace-root "/home/joe/code/futon6/.state/proof-frames/a93J02/apm-v2-a93J02-1775002596767", :artifacts {:proof-plan "/home/joe/code/futon6/.state/proof-frames/a93J02/apm-v2-a93J02-1775002596767/proof-plan.edn", :formal-alignment "/home/joe/code/futon6/.state/proof-frames/a93J02/apm-v2-a93J02-1775002596767/formal-alignment.edn", :changelog "/home/joe/code/futon6/.state/proof-frames/a93J02/apm-v2-a93J02-1775002596767/changelog.edn", :execute-notes "/home/joe/code/futon6/.state/proof-frames/a93J02/apm-v2-a93J02-1775002596767/execute.md", :workspace-readme "/home/joe/code/futon6/.state/proof-frames/a93J02/apm-v2-a93J02-1775002596767/README.md", :workspace-metadata "/home/joe/code/futon6/.state/proof-frames/a93J02/apm-v2-a93J02-1775002596767/workspace.json", :lean-main "/home/joe/code/apm-lean/ApmCanaries/Frames/A93J02/Apm_v2_a93J02_1775002596767/Main.lean", :lean-scratch "/home/joe/code/apm-lean/ApmCanaries/Frames/A93J02/Apm_v2_a93J02_1775002596767/Scratch.lean"}}, :proof/artifacts ["/home/joe/code/apm-lean/ApmCanaries/Frames/A93J02/Apm_v2_a93J02_1775002596767/Main.lean" "/home/joe/code/apm-lean/ApmCanaries/Frames/A93J02/Apm_v2_a93J02_1775002596767/Scratch.lean"], :proof/elapsed-ms 111572}